family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Sir </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Bernard Hogan-Howe, Tom Winsor and Olivia </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Pinkney</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">I hope this submission will be available to PASC members before the hearing as it anticipates some of the </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">assertions that will be made by those appearing before it and provides additional disturbing information obtained from serving front line officers.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">As the hearing progresses </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">there will be reassurances </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">from the Met representatives that</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> wi</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ll doubtless involv</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">e </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">phrases which will include the words ‘robust’, </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">‘rigorous, </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">‘integrity’ and </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">crime registrar.</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> Stephen </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Greenhalgh</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> will probably repeat the assertion that his own auditors will be ‘looking at the books’ to determine that</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> the recording of crime is </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">accurate. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Rank and file officers know only too well that the ‘devil lies in the detail’ and that only by examining the minutiae in the body of the crime reports, will it be possible to detect dubious crime recording. This will vary from borough to borough within th</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">e Met and quite possible from supervisor to supervisor. Those, such as outside auditors, not familiar with police parlance, procedures and the law will not be able to detect such nuances.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Those in the best position to articulate dubious practices are front</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> line rank and file officers who take reports from the public. </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Most will now not even attempt to ‘buck the system’ and will simply record the entry as they know the crime managers will wish it to be recorded. Thus robbery will frequently be recorded as the</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ft person unless the circumstances make it impracticable to do so. </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">This would be the case in the event of serious injury or clear evidence of a weapon</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> such as a knife</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> being used. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">The most recent Met staff </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">satisfaction </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">survey,</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> as the Commissioner would h</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ave to agree, shows an alarming lack of confidence by rank </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">and file</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">officers in</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> Met ACPO ranked management. The figures would probably be worse were it not for the fact that many officers do not trust the ‘guaranteed anonymity’ of such surveys. Similar res</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ults can be seen in respect of many other UK forces.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Even allowing f</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">or doubts by officers in relati</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">on to</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> anonymity, it would perhaps be a</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">n interesting exercise for the Met C</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ommissioner </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">or MOPAC </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">to conduct an </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">online independent survey </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">amongst </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">front line rank and file officers as to a) whether they believe crime figures are manipulated b) their ‘evidence’ for such a belief. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Last year, whilst in a </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">London </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ound shop, I became aware of a commotion and realised that a young male was complaining tha</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">t his phone had been stolen by stealth. One of the two suspects had left the store with the phone. The young male attempted to detain the other and was punched in the face causing a visible bleeding wound. I saw the suspect flee the shop as I </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">was </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">telephoni</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ng police. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">I drove round in a police vehicle looking for the second suspect without success. I was i</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">nformed by the officer </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">that the matter would be recorded as a </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">theft and assault</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> rather than the more </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">serious robbery</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">. I later checked the definition of r</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">obbery together with several ‘case stated’ </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">hearings </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">and there is no doubt that this incident comfortably comes within the robbery definition. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">resumably this ‘theft and assault’ would be buried within the ‘theft other’ figures rather than </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">amongst those ca</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">rrying </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">the ‘theft person’ definition.</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> It is ‘theft person’ category </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">however </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">where front line office</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">rs</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> allege many robbery offences are placed. As can be seen</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> from Attachment 1</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> there were nearly 50,000 </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">theft person</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> reports and given the different variations in policy amongst boroughs and individuals, these would have to be examined in depth to separate </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">robbery offences from </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">the genuine theft p</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ersons, </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">i.e.</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> ‘phone </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">snatches’ and</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">pick pocketing/’dipping’ </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">offences,</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> which</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> is another strand of ‘theft person</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">’ </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">that is of course </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">where such thefts are not entered into ‘property lost in the street’ records. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">To a non police auditor, it may well be that placing crimes, such as the one I partially witnessed, into the lesser categ</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ory, would be quite acceptable. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Recently</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> I spoke to two officers who have</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> spent some years on a local plain clothes squad dealing with street robberies.  </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">They were quite used to recording robberies as lesser offences but pointe</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">d out that when a suspect fo</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">r a robbery offence</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">which would</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> normally be reported as a theft person or theft and assault, was actually arrested at or near the scene, then the offence would be recorded as a robbery as it would show a </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">more serious </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">robbery clear up. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">The next piece of i</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">nformation from the officers stretched my credulity to the limit. The fact that one officer is a personal friend who joined the Met just weeks before me is the only reason why I feel confident </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">to include it</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> as fact. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">It would seem that if a suspect is arre</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">sted for a street robbery then not only is the individual robbed shown as the victim, but also included are his/her companions or other witnesses in close proximity to the incident, thus this would show as two, three, four robbery ‘clear ups’ as opposed to</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> one. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">This would not apply where </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">the suspect was not apprehended. T</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">he</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> individual robbed would be shown as the only victim with the possibility that the robbery could be recorded as a theft person or theft assault. </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> Witnesses would not be included as victi</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ms. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Sadly, such is the climate of fear within the Met that exists in relation to any officer who be considered a ‘whistleblower</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">’ I am unable to name even the borough </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">where </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">these of</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ficers perform duty </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">in case this leads to their identification. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Whilst ACPO ranked officers and PCC’s will officially ‘deplore’ any crime figure manipulation and </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">whereas </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">the Home office have ‘abolished’ targets, huge pressure exists on Met borough commanders </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">of Chief Superintendent rank </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">to reduce crime figures. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Tales </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">of ‘wire type’ grilling administered by certain known ACPO officers </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">abound throughout the Met and </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">are far too common to be</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">dismissed as </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">‘Chinese whispers.’ Chief Superintendent’s have been reduced to tears and indeed removed from their post</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> for failing to</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> bring those figures down. Bewildered officers at one west London borough came under the command of th</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ree Chief Superintendents during a period of </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">several weeks</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">This inevitably leads to downward pressure by Chief Superintendents upon their police supervis</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ory managers </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">who themselves feel that it is incumbent upon them to reduce crime figures if they wish to remain in post and/or advance their careers.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">The question of ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">whistleblowing</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">’ and indeed any conscientious form of </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">dissent,</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> as illustrated by the previo</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">us </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">PASC hearing</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> is clearly linked to the manipulation of crime figures. The assertion in the </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Met’s</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> recently</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> issued code of conduct in respect of pro</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">tection of </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">whistleblowers</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> has been</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> greeted with derision by rank and file officers.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">I have absolutely no do</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ubt that if the question of ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">whistleblowing</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">’ was added to any crime figure manipulation survey, as described above, more that 90% of rank and file officers would state that they would not have any faith in the syst</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">em other than in the most obvious </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">cases (m</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">oney being accepted from criminal elements in return for ‘favours’ or indeed money accepted from journalists). </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">The key question is how crime figure manipulation can be identified and dealt with given the fact that dubious practises have continued for deca</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">des. Using </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> police officers or police staff as crime registrars, hiring independent auditors who are unfamiliar with the vagaries of police crime reporting  using police or PCC funds or even </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">utilising </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">HMIC staff again who in all probability will be equally</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> unfamiliar with the above mentioned vagaries, will do little to inspire confidence.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">The answer perhaps lies with those former and current officers who have previously given evidence of crime figure manipulation and together with those of ACPO rank who </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">use</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> both overt and </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">dubious </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">furtive</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> methods to discourage whistleblowers whilst publically stating the opposite.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>